5. AI Conversation System
How It Works
Each door encounter is powered by the Claude API. The player's typed dialogue is sent with a system prompt that defines the NPC's personality, hidden desire, current emotional state, and running suspicion and warmth levels. The API returns a structured JSON response every turn.

JSON Response Format
{ "reply": "...", "suspicion": 2, "warmth": 4, "dealAccepted": false, "slamDoor": false }

Field
Type
Description
reply
String
What the NPC says out loud in the encounter
suspicion
Int 0-10
How suspicious the NPC is of the intern
warmth
Int 0-10
How receptive the NPC is to the pitch
dealAccepted
Boolean
Whether the NPC signed the soul acquisition form
slamDoor
Boolean
Whether the NPC immediately ends the conversation


Global Roleplay Preamble
Every NPC prompt is prepended with a global preamble that establishes the world, keeps characters in character, and enforces the JSON output format. Key rules include:
World is timeless — technology and old world aesthetics coexist naturally
Characters know what phones and games are but the town feels slightly out of time
NPCs are NOT AI — deny it naturally in character if asked
All replies 1 to 3 sentences maximum
No asterisk actions — just speak
Always end with the required JSON on its own line


6. The Performance Review Pressure System
Overview
There is no timer in Hell Inc. The pressure comes entirely from your choices — not the clock. Two things can end your assignment early: town suspicion hitting 100%, or your rejection rate getting bad enough that Gary pulls you from the field. The longer you stay in town the more suspicious residents become, but you are never racing a countdown. You are racing your own competence.

